A basic outline for how to install X86ElfInstrumentor.

1. System Requirements
Operating System        Linux
Binary Format           Elf
Architecture            IA32 or X64
Other                   To call instrumentation functions from a shared library
                        the system must have dynamic linking enabled. Also requires
                        the gnu linker to be used.


2. Add the following to your shell login script (assuming the installation is
at /path/to/x86inst/)

bash:
X86INST_ROOT=${HOME}/X86ElfInstrumentor
X86INST_LIB=${X86INST_ROOT}/lib
X86INST_BIN=${X86INST_ROOT}/bin
X86INST_LD_FLAGS="-Wl,--hash-style=sysv -Wl,-T,${X86INST_ROOT}/linker/x86inst_ld_script"
X86INST_LD=ld
X86INST_GFORT=gfortran
PATH=${PATH}:${X86INST_BIN}
export X86INST_ROOT
export X86INST_LIB
export X86INST_BIN
export X86INST_LD_FLAGS
export X86INST_LD
export X86INST_GFORT
export PATH

csh:
setenv X86INST_ROOT ${HOME}/X86ElfInstrumentor
setenv X86INST_LIB ${X86INST_ROOT}/lib
setenv X86INST_BIN ${X86INST_ROOT}/bin
setenv X86INST_LD_FLAGS "-Wl,--hash-style=sysv -Wl,-T,${X86INST_ROOT}/linker/x86inst_ld_script"
setenv X86INST_LD ld
setenv X86INST_GFORT gfortran
setenv PATH ${PATH}:${X86INST_BIN}

3. build 
`gmake` from the top-level directory

4. run
Examples:
x86inst --typ jbb --app testapps/dynTest.gnu
x86inst --lib lib --typ ide src/x86inst